1Ô∏è‚É£ CloudFront

Amazon CloudFront is a Content Delivery Network (CDN) service.
It delivers content to users with low latency by using edge locations.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Edge Locations

Edge locations are global data centers where content is cached.
They deliver content to users from the nearest location.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Origin

An origin is the source of the content.
Examples include S3 buckets, EC2 instances, or load balancers.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Caching

CloudFront caches content at edge locations.
This reduces load on the origin and improves performance.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Distribution

A distribution defines how content is delivered through CloudFront.
It links edge locations with the origin.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Security

CloudFront supports HTTPS, SSL/TLS, and AWS WAF integration.
It protects applications from common web attacks.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Access Control

CloudFront can restrict access using signed URLs and signed cookies.
Only authorized users can access private content.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Integration

CloudFront integrates with S3, Route 53, WAF, and Shield.
This helps build secure and scalable architectures.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Performance

CloudFront improves website speed and reduces latency.
It is ideal for global users.

üîü Use Cases

CloudFront is used for static websites, video streaming, APIs, and dynamic content delivery.
It improves performance and security.
